# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apoptosis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In contrast to necrosis, which is a form of traumatic cell death that results from acute cellular injury, apoptosis is a highly regulated and controlled process that confers advantages during an organism's life cycle.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] For example, the separation of fingers and toes in a developing human embryo occurs because cells between the digits undergo a form of apoptosis that is genetically determined.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Unlike necrosis, apoptosis produces cell fragments called apoptotic bodies that phagocytes are able to engulf and remove before the contents of the cell can spill out onto surrounding cells and cause damage to them.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Because apoptosis cannot stop once it has begun, it is a highly regulated process.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis can be initiated through one of two pathways.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In the *intrinsic pathway* the cell kills itself because it senses cell stress, while in the *extrinsic pathway* the cell kills itself because of signals from other cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Weak external signals may also activate the intrinsic pathway of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Both pathways induce cell death by activating caspases, which are proteases, or enzymes that degrade proteins.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The two pathways both activate initiator caspases, which then activate executioner caspases, which then kill the cell by degrading proteins indiscriminately.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In addition to its importance as a biological phenomenon, defective apoptotic processes have been implicated in a wide variety of diseases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Excessive apoptosis causes atrophy, whereas an insufficient amount results in uncontrolled cell proliferation, such as cancer.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Some factors, like Fas receptors and caspases, promote apoptosis, while some members of the Bcl-2 family of proteins inhibit apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] German scientist Carl Vogt was first to describe the principle of apoptosis in 1842.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In 1885, anatomist Walther Flemming delivered a more precise description of the process of programmed cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, it was not until 1965 that the topic was resurrected.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] While studying tissues using electron microscopy, John Kerr at the University of Queensland was able to distinguish apoptosis from traumatic cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Following the publication of a paper describing the phenomenon, Kerr was invited to join Alastair Currie, as well as Andrew Wyllie, who was Currie's graduate student, at the University of Aberdeen.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In 1972, the trio published a seminal article in the *British Journal of Cancer*.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Kerr had initially used the term programmed cell necrosis, but in the article, the process of natural cell death was called *apoptosis*.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Kerr, Wyllie and Currie credited James Cormack, a professor of Greek language at University of Aberdeen, with suggesting the term apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Kerr received the Paul Ehrlich and Ludwig Darmstaedter Prize on March 14, 2000, for his description of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] He shared the prize with Boston biologist H.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] For many years, neither "apoptosis" nor "programmed cell death" was a highly cited term.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Two discoveries brought cell death from obscurity to a major field of research: identification of the first component of the cell death control and effector mechanisms, and linkage of abnormalities in cell death to human disease, in particular cancer.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This occurred in 1988 when it was shown that BCL2, the gene responsible for follicular lymphoma, encoded a protein that inhibited cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The 2002 Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to Sydney Brenner, H.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Robert Horvitz and John Sulston for their work identifying genes that control apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The genes were identified by studies in the nematode *C. elegans* and homologues of these genes function in humans to regulate apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In Greek, apoptosis translates to the "falling off" of leaves from a tree.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cormack, professor of Greek language, reintroduced the term for medical use as it had a medical meaning for the Greeks over two thousand years before.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Hippocrates used the term to mean "the falling off of the bones".
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Galen extended its meaning to "the dropping of the scabs".
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cormack was no doubt aware of this usage when he suggested the name.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Debate continues over the correct pronunciation, with opinion divided between a pronunciation with the second *p* silent (/æpəˈtoʊsɪs/ *ap-ə-TOH-sis*) and the second *p* pronounced (/eɪpəpˈtoʊsɪs/ ⓘ).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In English, the *p* of the Greek *-pt-* consonant cluster is typically silent at the beginning of a word (e.g. pterodactyl, Ptolemy), but articulated when used in combining forms preceded by a vowel, as in helicopter or the orders of insects: diptera, lepidoptera, etc.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The initiation of apoptosis is tightly regulated by activation mechanisms, because once apoptosis has begun, it inevitably leads to the death of the cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The two best-understood activation mechanisms are the intrinsic pathway (also called the mitochondrial pathway) and the extrinsic pathway.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The *intrinsic pathway* is activated by intracellular signals generated when cells are stressed and depends on the release of proteins from the intermembrane space of mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The *extrinsic pathway* is activated by extracellular ligands binding to cell-surface death receptors, which leads to the formation of the death-inducing signaling complex (DISC).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A cell initiates intracellular apoptotic signaling in response to a stress, which may bring about cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A number of cellular components, such as poly ADP ribose polymerase, may also help regulate apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Single cell fluctuations have been observed in experimental studies of stress induced apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Before the actual process of cell death is precipitated by enzymes, apoptotic signals must cause regulatory proteins to initiate the apoptosis pathway.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This step allows those signals to cause cell death, or the process to be stopped, should the cell no longer need to die.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Several proteins are involved, but two main methods of regulation have been identified: the targeting of mitochondria functionality, or directly transducing the signal via adaptor proteins to the apoptotic mechanisms.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] An extrinsic pathway for initiation identified in several toxin studies is an increase in calcium concentration within a cell caused by drug activity, which also can cause apoptosis via a calcium binding protease calpain.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The intrinsic pathway is also known as the mitochondrial pathway.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Mitochondria are essential to multicellular life.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Without them, a cell ceases to respire aerobically and quickly dies.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This fact forms the basis for some apoptotic pathways.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptotic proteins that target mitochondria affect them in different ways.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] They may cause mitochondrial swelling through the formation of membrane pores, or they may increase the permeability of the mitochondrial membrane and cause apoptotic effectors to leak out.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] There is also a growing body of evidence indicating that nitric oxide is able to induce apoptosis by helping to dissipate the membrane potential of mitochondria and therefore make it more permeable.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Nitric oxide has been implicated in initiating and inhibiting apoptosis through its possible action as a signal molecule of subsequent pathways that activate apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] During apoptosis, cytochrome *c* is released from mitochondria through the actions of the proteins Bax and Bak.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The mechanism of this release is enigmatic, but appears to stem from a multitude of Bax/Bak homo- and hetero-dimers of Bax/Bak inserted into the outer membrane.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Once cytochrome *c* is released it binds with Apoptotic protease activating factor – 1 (*Apaf-1*) and ATP, which then bind to *pro-caspase-9* to create a protein complex known as an apoptosome.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The apoptosome cleaves the pro-caspase to its active form of caspase-9, which in turn cleaves and activates pro-caspase into the effector *caspase-3*.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Mitochondria also release proteins known as SMACs (second mitochondria-derived activator of caspases) into the cell's cytosol following the increase in permeability of the mitochondria membranes.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] SMAC binds to *proteins that inhibit apoptosis* (IAPs) thereby deactivating them, and preventing the IAPs from arresting the process and therefore allowing apoptosis to proceed.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] IAP also normally suppresses the activity of a group of cysteine proteases called caspases, which carry out the degradation of the cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Therefore, the actual degradation enzymes can be seen to be indirectly regulated by mitochondrial permeability.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Two theories of the direct initiation of apoptotic mechanisms in mammals have been suggested: the *TNF-induced* (tumor necrosis factor) model and the *Fas-Fas ligand-mediated* model, both involving receptors of the *TNF receptor* (TNFR) family coupled to extrinsic signals.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] TNF is a cytokine produced mainly by activated macrophages, and is the major extrinsic mediator of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Most cells in the human body have two receptors for TNF: TNFR1 and TNFR2.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The binding of TNF to TNFR1 has been shown to initiate the pathway that leads to caspase activation via the intermediate membrane proteins TNF receptor-associated death domain (TRADD) and Fas-associated death domain protein (FADD). cIAP1/2 can inhibit TNF signaling by binding to TRAF2.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] FLIP inhibits the activation of caspase-8.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Binding of this receptor can also indirectly lead to the activation of transcription factors involved in cell survival and inflammatory responses.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, signalling through TNFR1 might also induce apoptosis in a caspase-independent manner.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The link between TNF and apoptosis shows why an abnormal production of TNF plays a fundamental role in several human diseases, especially in autoimmune diseases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The TNF receptor superfamily also includes death receptors (DRs), such as DR4 and DR5.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These receptors bind to the protein TRAIL and mediate apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis is known to be one of the primary mechanisms of targeted cancer therapy.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Luminescent iridium complex-peptide hybrids (IPHs) have recently been designed, which mimic TRAIL and bind to death receptors on cancer cells, thereby inducing their apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The fas receptor (First apoptosis signal) – (also known as *Apo-1* or *CD95*) is a transmembrane protein of the TNF family which binds the Fas ligand (FasL).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The interaction between Fas and FasL results in the formation of the *death-inducing signaling complex* (DISC), which contains the FADD, caspase-8 and caspase-10.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In some types of cells (type I), processed caspase-8 directly activates other members of the caspase family, and triggers the execution of apoptosis of the cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In other types of cells (type II), the *Fas*-DISC starts a feedback loop that spirals into increasing release of proapoptotic factors from mitochondria and the amplified activation of caspase-8.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Following *TNF-R1* and *Fas* activation in mammalian cells a balance between proapoptotic (BAX, BID, BAK, or BAD) and anti-apoptotic (*Bcl-Xl* and *Bcl-2*) members of the *Bcl-2* family are established.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This balance is the proportion of proapoptotic homodimers that form in the outer-membrane of the mitochondrion.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The proapoptotic homodimers are required to make the mitochondrial membrane permeable for the release of caspase activators such as cytochrome c and SMAC.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Control of proapoptotic proteins under normal cell conditions of nonapoptotic cells is incompletely understood, but in general, Bax or Bak are activated by the activation of BH3-only proteins, part of the Bcl-2 family.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Caspases play the central role in the transduction of ER apoptotic signals.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Caspases are proteins that are highly conserved, cysteine-dependent aspartate-specific proteases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] There are two types of caspases: initiator caspases (caspases 2, 8, 9, 10, 11, and 12) and effector caspases (caspases 3, 6, and 7).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The activation of initiator caspases requires binding to specific oligomeric activator protein.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These active initiator caspases activate the effector caspases through proteolytic cleavage.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The active effector caspases then proteolytically degrade a host of intracellular proteins to carry out the cell death program.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] There also exists a caspase-independent apoptotic pathway that is mediated by AIF (apoptosis-inducing factor).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The frog *Xenopus laevis* serves as an ideal model system for the study of the mechanisms of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In fact, iodine and thyroxine also stimulate the spectacular apoptosis of the cells of the larval gills, tail and fins in amphibian's metamorphosis, and stimulate the evolution of their nervous system transforming the aquatic, vegetarian tadpole into the terrestrial, carnivorous frog.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Negative regulation of apoptosis inhibits cell death signaling pathways, helping tumors to evade cell death and developing drug resistance.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The ratio between anti-apoptotic (Bcl-2) and pro-apoptotic (Bax) proteins determines whether a cell lives or dies.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Many families of proteins act as negative regulators categorized into either antiapoptotic factors, such as IAPs and Bcl-2 proteins or prosurvival factors like cFLIP, BNIP3, FADD, Akt, and NF-κB.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Many pathways and signals lead to apoptosis, but these converge on a single mechanism that actually causes the death of the cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] After a cell receives stimulus, it undergoes organized degradation of cellular organelles by activated proteolytic caspases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In addition to the destruction of cellular organelles, mRNA is rapidly and globally degraded by a mechanism that is not yet fully characterized. mRNA decay is triggered very early in apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A cell undergoing apoptosis shows a series of characteristic morphological changes.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The cytoplasm appears dense, and the organelles appear tightly packed.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Chromatin undergoes condensation into compact patches against the nuclear envelope (also known as the perinuclear envelope) in a process known as pyknosis, a hallmark of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The nuclear envelope becomes discontinuous and the DNA inside it is fragmented in a process referred to as karyorrhexis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The nucleus breaks into several discrete *chromatin bodies* or *nucleosomal units* due to the degradation of DNA.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis progresses quickly and its products are quickly removed, making it difficult to detect or visualize on classical histology sections.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] During karyorrhexis, endonuclease activation leaves short DNA fragments, regularly spaced in size.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These give a characteristic "laddered" appearance on agar gel after electrophoresis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Tests for DNA laddering differentiate apoptosis from ischemic or toxic cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Before the apoptotic cell is disposed of, there is a process of disassembly.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Formation of membrane protrusions: Some cell types, under specific conditions, may develop different types of long, thin extensions of the cell membrane called membrane protrusions.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Three types have been described: microtubule spikes, **apoptopodia** (*feet of death*), and **beaded apoptopodia** (the latter having a beads-on-a-string appearance).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Pannexin 1 is an important component of membrane channels involved in the formation of apoptopodia and beaded apoptopodia.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Fragmentation: The cell breaks apart into multiple vesicles called *apoptotic bodies*, which undergo phagocytosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The plasma membrane protrusions may help bring apoptotic bodies closer to phagocytes.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The removal of dead cells by neighboring phagocytic cells has been termed efferocytosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Dying cells that undergo the final stages of apoptosis display apoptotic-cell associated molecular patterns (ACAMPs), such as phosphatidylserine on the outer leaflet of the cell membrane.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Phosphatidylserine is normally found on the inner leaflet surface of the plasma membrane, but is redistributed during apoptosis to the extracellular surface by a protein known as scramblase.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These molecules mark the cell for phagocytosis by cells possessing the appropriate receptors, such as macrophages.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The removal of dying cells by phagocytes occurs in an orderly manner without eliciting an inflammatory response.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] During apoptosis cellular RNA and DNA are separated from each other and sorted to different apoptotic bodies; separation of RNA is initiated as nucleolar segregation.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Many knock-outs have been made in the apoptosis pathways to test the function of each of the proteins.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Several caspases, in addition to APAF1 and FADD, have been mutated to determine the new phenotype.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In order to create a tumor necrosis factor (TNF) knockout, an exon containing the nucleotides 3704–5364 was removed from the gene.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This exon encodes a portion of the mature TNF domain, as well as the leader sequence, which is a highly conserved region necessary for proper intracellular processing.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] TNF-/- mice develop normally and have no gross structural or morphological abnormalities.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, upon immunization with SRBC (sheep red blood cells), these mice demonstrated a deficiency in the maturation of an antibody response; they were able to generate normal levels of IgM, but could not develop specific IgG levels.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apaf-1 is the protein that turns on caspase 9 by cleavage to begin the caspase cascade that leads to apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Since a -/- mutation in the APAF-1 gene is embryonic lethal, a gene trap strategy was used in order to generate an APAF-1 -/- mouse.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This assay is used to disrupt gene function by creating an intragenic gene fusion.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] When an APAF-1 gene trap is introduced into cells, many morphological changes occur, such as spina bifida, the persistence of interdigital webs, and open brain.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In addition, after embryonic day 12.5, the brain of the embryos showed several structural changes.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] APAF-1 cells are protected from apoptosis stimuli such as irradiation.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A BAX-1 knock-out mouse exhibits normal forebrain formation and a decreased programmed cell death in some neuronal populations and in the spinal cord, leading to an increase in motor neurons.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The caspase proteins are integral parts of the apoptosis pathway, so it follows that knock-outs made have varying damaging results.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A caspase 9 knock-out leads to a severe brain malformation .
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A caspase 8 knock-out leads to cardiac failure and thus embryonic lethality .
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, with the use of cre-lox technology, a caspase 8 knock-out has been created that exhibits an increase in peripheral T cells, an impaired T cell response, and a defect in neural tube closure .
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These mice were found to be resistant to apoptosis mediated by CD95, TNFR, etc. but not resistant to apoptosis caused by UV irradiation, chemotherapeutic drugs, and other stimuli.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Finally, a caspase 3 knock-out was characterized by ectopic cell masses in the brain and abnormal apoptotic features such as membrane blebbing or nuclear fragmentation .
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Label-free live cell imaging, time-lapse microscopy, flow fluorocytometry, and transmission electron microscopy can be used to compare apoptotic and necrotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] There are also various biochemical techniques for analysis of cell surface markers (phosphatidylserine exposure versus cell permeability by flow cytometry), cellular markers such as DNA fragmentation (flow cytometry), caspase activation, Bid cleavage, and cytochrome c release (Western blotting).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Supernatant screening for caspases, HMGB1, and cytokeratin 18 release can identify primary from secondary necrotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, no distinct surface or biochemical markers of necrotic cell death have been identified yet, and only negative markers are available.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These include absence of apoptotic markers (caspase activation, cytochrome c release, and oligonucleosomal DNA fragmentation) and differential kinetics of cell death markers (phosphatidylserine exposure and cell membrane permeabilization).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A selection of techniques that can be used to distinguish apoptosis from necroptotic cells could be found in these references.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The various types of apoptotic pathways contain a multitude of different biochemical components, many of them not yet understood.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] As a pathway is more or less sequential in nature, removing or modifying one component leads to an effect in another.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In a living organism, this can have disastrous effects, often in the form of disease or disorder.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A discussion of every disease caused by modification of the various apoptotic pathways would be impractical, but the underlying concept is the same: The normal functioning of the pathway has been disrupted in such a way as to impair the ability of the cell to undergo normal apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This results in a cell that lives past its "use-by date" and can replicate and pass on any faulty machinery to its progeny, increasing the likelihood of the cell's becoming cancerous or diseased.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] A recently described example of this concept in action can be seen in the development of a lung cancer called NCI-H460.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The *X-linked inhibitor of apoptosis protein* (XIAP) is overexpressed in cells of the H460 cell line.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] XIAPs bind to the processed form of caspase-9 and suppress the activity of apoptotic activator cytochrome c; therefore, overexpression leads to a decrease in the number of proapoptotic agonists.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] As a consequence, the balance of anti-apoptotic and proapoptotic effectors is upset in favour of the former, and the damaged cells continue to replicate despite being directed to die.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Defects in regulation of apoptosis in cancer cells occur often at the level of control of transcription factors.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] As a particular example, defects in molecules that control transcription factor NF-κB in cancer change the mode of transcriptional regulation and the response to apoptotic signals, to curtail dependence on the tissue that the cell belongs.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This degree of independence from external survival signals, can enable cancer metastasis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The tumor-suppressor protein p53 accumulates when DNA is damaged due to a chain of biochemical factors.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Any disruption to the regulation of the *p53* or interferon genes will result in impaired apoptosis and the possible formation of tumors.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Inhibition of apoptosis can result in a number of cancers, inflammatory diseases, and viral infections.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] It was originally believed that the associated accumulation of cells was due to an increase in cellular proliferation, but it is now known that it is also due to a decrease in cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The most common of these diseases is cancer, the disease of excessive cellular proliferation, which is often characterized by an overexpression of IAP family members.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] As a result, the malignant cells experience an abnormal response to apoptosis induction: Cycle-regulating genes (such as p53, ras or c-myc) are mutated or inactivated in diseased cells, and further genes (such as bcl-2) also modify their expression in tumors.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Some apoptotic factors are vital during mitochondrial respiration e.g. cytochrome C.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Pathological inactivation of apoptosis in cancer cells is correlated with frequent respiratory metabolic shifts toward glycolysis (an observation known as the "Warburg hypothesis".
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis in HeLa cells is inhibited by proteins produced by the cell; these inhibitory proteins target retinoblastoma tumor-suppressing proteins.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These tumor-suppressing proteins regulate the cell cycle, but are rendered inactive when bound to an inhibitory protein.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HPV E6 and E7 are inhibitory proteins expressed by the human papillomavirus, HPV being responsible for the formation of the cervical tumor from which HeLa cells are derived.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HPV E6 causes p53, which regulates the cell cycle, to become inactive.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HPV E7 binds to retinoblastoma tumor suppressing proteins and limits its ability to control cell division.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These two inhibitory proteins are partially responsible for HeLa cells' immortality by inhibiting apoptosis to occur.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The main method of treatment for potential death from signaling-related diseases involves either increasing or decreasing the susceptibility of apoptosis in diseased cells, depending on whether the disease is caused by either the inhibition of or excess apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] For instance, treatments aim to restore apoptosis to treat diseases with deficient cell death and to increase the apoptotic threshold to treat diseases involved with excessive cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] To stimulate apoptosis, one can increase the number of death receptor ligands (such as TNF or TRAIL), antagonize the anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 pathway, or introduce Smac mimetics to inhibit the inhibitor (IAPs).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The addition of agents such as Herceptin, Iressa, or Gleevec works to stop cells from cycling and causes apoptosis activation by blocking growth and survival signaling further upstream.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Finally, adding p53-MDM2 complexes displaces p53 and activates the p53 pathway, leading to cell cycle arrest and apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Many different methods can be used either to stimulate or to inhibit apoptosis in various places along the death signaling pathway.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis is a multi-step, multi-pathway cell-death programme that is inherent in every cell of the body.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In cancer, the apoptosis cell-division ratio is altered.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cancer treatment by chemotherapy and irradiation kills target cells primarily by inducing apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] On the other hand, loss of control of cell death (resulting in excess apoptosis) can lead to neurodegenerative diseases, hematologic diseases, and tissue damage.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Neurons that rely on mitochondrial respiration undergo apoptosis in neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] (an observation known as the "Inverse Warburg hypothesis").
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Moreover, there is an inverse epidemiological comorbidity between neurodegenerative diseases and cancer.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The progression of HIV is directly linked to excess, unregulated apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In a healthy individual, the number of CD4+ lymphocytes is in balance with the cells generated by the bone marrow; however, in HIV-positive patients, this balance is lost due to an inability of the bone marrow to regenerate CD4+ cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In the case of HIV, CD4+ lymphocytes die at an accelerated rate through uncontrolled apoptosis, when stimulated.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] At the molecular level, hyperactive apoptosis can be caused by defects in signaling pathways that regulate the Bcl-2 family proteins.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Increased expression of apoptotic proteins such as BIM, or their decreased proteolysis, leads to cell death and can cause a number of pathologies, depending on the cells where excessive activity of BIM occurs.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cancer cells can escape apoptosis through mechanisms that suppress BIM expression or by increased proteolysis of BIM.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Treatments aiming to inhibit works to block specific caspases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Finally, the Akt protein kinase promotes cell survival through two pathways.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Akt phosphorylates and inhibits Bad (a Bcl-2 family member), causing Bad to interact with the 14-3-3 scaffold, resulting in Bcl dissociation and thus cell survival.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Akt also activates IKKα, which leads to NF-κB activation and cell survival.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Active NF-κB induces the expression of anti-apoptotic genes such as Bcl-2, resulting in inhibition of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] NF-κB has been found to play both an antiapoptotic role and a proapoptotic role depending on the stimuli utilized and the cell type.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The progression of the human immunodeficiency virus infection into AIDS is due primarily to the depletion of CD4+ T-helper lymphocytes in a manner that is too rapid for the body's bone marrow to replenish the cells, leading to a compromised immune system.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HIV may increase the level of cellular proteins that prompt Fas-mediated apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HIV proteins decrease the amount of CD4 glycoprotein marker present on the cell membrane.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Released viral particles and proteins present in extracellular fluid are able to induce apoptosis in nearby "bystander" T helper cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HIV decreases the production of molecules involved in marking the cell for apoptosis, giving the virus time to replicate and continue releasing apoptotic agents and virions into the surrounding tissue.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The infected CD4+ cell may also receive the death signal from a cytotoxic T cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cells may also die as direct consequences of viral infections.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HIV-1 expression induces tubular cell G2/M arrest and apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The progression from HIV to AIDS is not immediate or even necessarily rapid; HIV's cytotoxic activity toward CD4+ lymphocytes is classified as AIDS once a given patient's CD4+ cell count falls below 200.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] By suppressing viral budding, the researchers were able to trap the HIV virus in the cell and allow for the cell to undergo apoptosis (natural cell death).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Associate Professor Mikako Fujita has stated that the approach is not yet available to HIV patients because the research team has to conduct further research on combining the drug therapy that currently exists with this "Lock-in and apoptosis" approach to lead to complete recovery from HIV.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Viral induction of apoptosis occurs when one or several cells of a living organism are infected with a virus, leading to cell death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Cell death in organisms is necessary for the normal development of cells and the cell cycle maturation.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] It is also important in maintaining the regular functions and activities of cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Canine distemper virus (CDV) is known to cause apoptosis in central nervous system and lymphoid tissue of infected dogs in vivo and in vitro.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis caused by CDV is typically induced via the extrinsic pathway, which activates caspases that disrupt cellular function and eventually leads to the cells death.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In normal cells, CDV activates caspase-8 first, which works as the initiator protein followed by the executioner protein caspase-3.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, apoptosis induced by CDV in HeLa cells does not involve the initiator protein caspase-8.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] HeLa cell apoptosis caused by CDV follows a different mechanism than that in vero cell lines.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This change in the caspase cascade suggests CDV induces apoptosis via the intrinsic pathway, excluding the need for the initiator caspase-8.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The executioner protein is instead activated by the internal stimuli caused by viral infection not a caspase cascade.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The Oropouche virus (OROV) is found in the family *Bunyaviridae*.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The study of apoptosis brought on by *Bunyaviridae* was initiated in 1996, when it was observed that apoptosis was induced by the La Crosse virus into the kidney cells of baby hamsters and into the brains of baby mice.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] OROV is a disease that is transmitted between humans by the biting midge (*Culicoides paraensis*).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] It is referred to as a zoonotic arbovirus and causes febrile illness, characterized by the onset of a sudden fever known as Oropouche fever.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The Oropouche virus also causes disruption in cultured cells – cells that are cultivated in distinct and specific conditions.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] An example of this can be seen in HeLa cells, whereby the cells begin to degenerate shortly after they are infected.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] With the use of gel electrophoresis, it can be observed that OROV causes DNA fragmentation in HeLa cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] It can be interpreted by counting, measuring, and analyzing the cells of the Sub/G1 cell population.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] When HeLA cells are infected with OROV, the cytochrome C is released from the membrane of the mitochondria, into the cytosol of the cells.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] This type of interaction shows that apoptosis is activated via an intrinsic pathway.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In order for apoptosis to occur within OROV, viral uncoating, viral internalization, along with the replication of cells is necessary.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Apoptosis in some viruses is activated by extracellular stimuli.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] However, studies have demonstrated that the OROV infection causes apoptosis to be activated through intracellular stimuli and involves the mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Many viruses encode proteins that can inhibit apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Several viruses encode viral homologs of Bcl-2.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] These homologs can inhibit proapoptotic proteins such as BAX and BAK, which are essential for the activation of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Examples of viral Bcl-2 proteins include the Epstein-Barr virus BHRF1 protein and the adenovirus E1B 19K protein.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Some viruses express caspase inhibitors that inhibit caspase activity and an example is the CrmA protein of cowpox viruses.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Whilst a number of viruses can block the effects of TNF and Fas.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] For example, the M-T2 protein of myxoma viruses can bind TNF preventing it from binding the TNF receptor and inducing a response.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Furthermore, many viruses express p53 inhibitors that can bind p53 and inhibit its transcriptional transactivation activity.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] As a consequence, p53 cannot induce apoptosis, since it cannot induce the expression of proapoptotic proteins.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The adenovirus E1B-55K protein and the hepatitis B virus HBx protein are examples of viral proteins that can perform such a function.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Viruses can remain intact from apoptosis in particular in the latter stages of infection.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] They can be exported in the *apoptotic bodies* that pinch off from the surface of the dying cell, and the fact that they are engulfed by phagocytes prevents the initiation of a host response.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Programmed cell death in plants has a number of molecular similarities to that of animal apoptosis, but it also has differences, notable ones being the presence of a cell wall and the lack of an immune system that removes the pieces of the dead cell.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Instead of an immune response, the dying cell synthesizes substances to break itself down and places them in a vacuole that ruptures as the cell dies.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Additionally, plants do not contain phagocytic cells, which are essential in the process of breaking down and removing apoptotic bodies.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Whether this whole process resembles animal apoptosis closely enough to warrant using the name *apoptosis* (as opposed to the more general *programmed cell death*) is unclear.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] The characterization of the caspases allowed the development of caspase inhibitors, which can be used to determine whether a cellular process involves active caspases.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Using these inhibitors, it was discovered that cells can die while displaying a morphology similar to apoptosis without caspase activation.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Later studies linked this phenomenon to the release of AIF (apoptosis-inducing factor) from the mitochondria and its translocation into the nucleus mediated by its NLS (nuclear localization signal).
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] Inside the mitochondria, AIF is anchored to the inner membrane.
[src:apoptosis/apoptosis] In order to be released, the protein is cleaved by a calcium-dependent calpain protease.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Four forms of autophagy have been identified: macroautophagy, microautophagy, chaperone-mediated autophagy (CMA), and crinophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In crinophagy (the least well-known and researched form of autophagy), unnecessary secretory granules are degraded and recycled.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In disease, autophagy has been seen as an adaptive response to stress, promoting survival of the cell; but in other cases, it appears to promote cell death and morbidity.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In the extreme case of starvation, the breakdown of cellular components promotes cellular survival by maintaining cellular energy levels.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The word "autophagy" was in existence and frequently used from the middle of the 19th century.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In its present usage, the term autophagy was coined by Belgian biochemist Christian de Duve in 1963 based on his discovery of the functions of lysosome.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The identification of autophagy-related genes in yeast in the 1990s allowed researchers to deduce the mechanisms of autophagy, which eventually led to the award of the 2016 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine to Japanese researcher Yoshinori Ohsumi.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy was first observed by Keith R.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Porter and his student Thomas Ashford at the Rockefeller Institute.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In January 1962 they reported an increased number of lysosomes in rat liver cells after the addition of glucagon, and that some displaced lysosomes towards the centre of the cell contained other cell organelles such as mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] They called this autolysis after Christian de Duve and Alex B.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] However Porter and Ashford wrongly interpreted their data as lysosome formation (ignoring the pre-existing organelles).
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Lysosomes could not be cell organelles, but part of cytoplasm such as mitochondria, and that hydrolytic enzymes were produced by microbodies.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In 1963 Hruban, Spargo and colleagues published a detailed ultrastructural description of "focal cytoplasmic degradation", which referenced a 1955 German study of injury-induced sequestration.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Inspired by this discovery, de Duve christened the phenomena "autophagy".
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Unlike Porter and Ashford, de Duve conceived the term as a part of lysosomal function while describing the role of glucagon as a major inducer of cell degradation in the liver.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] With his student Russell Deter, he established that lysosomes are responsible for glucagon-induced autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This was the first time the fact that lysosomes are the sites of intracellular autophagy was established.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In the 1990s several groups of scientists independently discovered autophagy-related genes using the budding yeast.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Notably, Yoshinori Ohsumi and Michael Thumm examined starvation-induced non-selective autophagy; in the meantime, Daniel J.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Klionsky discovered the cytoplasm-to-vacuole targeting (CVT) pathway, which is a form of selective autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] They soon found that they were in fact looking at essentially the same pathway, just from different angles.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Initially, the genes discovered by these and other yeast groups were given different names (APG, AUT, CVT, GSA, PAG, PAZ, and PDD).
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] A unified nomenclature was advocated in 2003 by the yeast researchers to use ATG to denote autophagy genes.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The 2016 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to Yoshinori Ohsumi, although some have pointed out that if there is only one recipient of the award, it must be Ohsumi, but that the award could have been more inclusive.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The field of autophagy research experienced accelerated growth at the turn of the 21st century.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Knowledge of ATG genes provided scientists more convenient tools to dissect functions of autophagy in human health and disease.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In 1999, a landmark discovery connecting autophagy with cancer was published by Beth Levine's group.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] To this date, relationship between cancer and autophagy continues to be a main theme of autophagy research.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The roles of autophagy in neurodegeneration and immune defense also received considerable attention.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In 2003, the first Gordon Research Conference on autophagy was held at Waterville.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In 2005, Daniel J Klionsky launched *Autophagy*, a scientific journal dedicated to this field.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The first Keystone Symposia on autophagy was held in 2007 at Monterey.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In 2008, Carol A Mercer created a BHMT fusion protein (GST-BHMT), which showed starvation-induced site-specific fragmentation in cell lines.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The degradation of betaine homocysteine methyltransferase (BHMT), a metabolic enzyme, could be used to assess autophagy flux in mammalian cells.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Macro, micro, and Chaperone mediated autophagy are mediated by autophagy-related genes and their associated enzymes.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Macroautophagy is then divided into bulk and selective autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In the selective autophagy is the autophagy of organelles; mitophagy, lipophagy, pexophagy, chlorophagy, ribophagy and others.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy targets genus-specific proteins, so orthologous proteins which share sequence homology with each other are recognized as substrates by a particular autophagy targeting protein.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] There exists a complementarity of autophagy targeting proteins which potentially increase infection risk upon mutation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The lack of overlap among the targets of the 3 autophagy proteins and the large overlap in terms of the genera show that autophagy could target different sets of bacterial proteins from the same pathogen.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] On one hand, the redundancy in targeting the same genera is beneficial for robust pathogen recognition.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] But, on the other hand, the complementarity in the specific bacterial proteins could make the host more susceptible to chronic disorders and infections if the gene encoding one of the autophagy targeting proteins becomes mutated, and the autophagy system is overloaded or suffers other malfunctions.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Moreover, autophagy targets virulence factors and virulence factors responsible for more general functions such as nutrient acquisition and motility are recognized by multiple autophagy targeting proteins.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] And the specialized virulence factors such as autolysins, and iron sequestering proteins are potentially recognized uniquely by a single autophagy targeting protein.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The autophagy proteins CALCOCO2/NDP52 and MAP1LC3/LC3 may have evolved specifically to target pathogens or pathogenic proteins for autophagic degradation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] While SQSTM1/p62 targets more generic bacterial proteins containing a target motif but not related to virulence.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] On the other hand, bacterial proteins from various pathogenic genera are also able to modulate autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] There are genus-specific patterns in the phases of autophagy that are potentially regulated by a given pathogen group.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Some autophagy phases can only be modulated by particular pathogens, while some phases are modulated by multiple pathogen genera.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Some of the interplay-related bacterial proteins have proteolytic and post-translational activity such as phosphorylation and ubiquitination and can interfere with the activity of autophagy proteins.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] To give specific examples, the UKL1 enzyme (kinase complex) induces autophagosome biogenesis, and ATG13 (Autophagy-related protein 13) is required for phagosome formation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Prior to 2003, ten or more names were used, but after this point a unified nomenclature was devised by fungal autophagy researchers.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The first autophagy genes were identified by genetic screens conducted in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Following their identification those genes were functionally characterized and their orthologs in a variety of different organisms were identified and studied.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Today, thirty-six Atg proteins have been classified as especially important for autophagy, of which 18 belong to the core machinery.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In mammals, amino acid sensing and additional signals such as growth factors and reactive oxygen species regulate the activity of the protein kinases mTOR and AMPK.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] These two kinases regulate autophagy through inhibitory phosphorylation of the Unc-51-like kinases ULK1 and ULK2 (mammalian homologues of Atg1).
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Induction of autophagy results in the dephosphorylation and activation of the ULK kinases.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] ULK is part of a protein complex containing Atg13, Atg101 and FIP200.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] ULK phosphorylates and activates Beclin-1 (mammalian homologue of Atg6), which is also part of a protein complex.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The autophagy-inducible Beclin-1 complex contains the proteins PIK3R4(p150), Atg14L and the class III phosphatidylinositol 3-phosphate kinase (PI(3)K) Vps34.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The active ULK and Beclin-1 complexes re-localize to the site of autophagosome initiation, the phagophore, where they both contribute to the activation of downstream autophagy components.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Once active, VPS34 phosphorylates the lipid phosphatidylinositol to generate phosphatidylinositol 3-phosphate (PtdIns(3)P) on the surface of the phagophore.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The generated PtdIns(3)P is used as a docking point for proteins harboring a PtdIns(3)P binding motif.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] WIPI2, a PtdIns(3)P binding protein of the WIPI (WD-repeat protein interacting with phosphoinositides) protein family, was recently shown to physically bind ATG16L1.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Atg16L1 is a member of an E3-like protein complex involved in one of two ubiquitin-like conjugation systems essential for autophagosome formation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The FIP200 cis-Golgi-derived membranes fuse with ATG16L1-positive endosomal membranes to form the prophagophore termed HyPAS (hybrid pre-autophagosomal structure).
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] ATG16L1 binding to WIPI2 mediates ATG16L1's activity.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This leads to downstream conversion of prophagophore into ATG8-positive phagophore via a ubiquitin-like conjugation system.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The first of the two ubiquitin-like conjugation systems involved in autophagy covalently binds the ubiquitin-like protein Atg12 to Atg5.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The resulting conjugate protein then binds ATG16L1 to form an E3-like complex which functions as part of the second ubiquitin-like conjugation system.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This complex binds and activates Atg3, which covalently attaches mammalian homologues of the ubiquitin-like yeast protein ATG8 (LC3A-C, GATE16, and GABARAPL1-3), the most studied being LC3 proteins, to the lipid phosphatidylethanolamine (PE) on the surface of autophagosomes.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Lipidated LC3 contributes to the closure of autophagosomes, and enables the docking of specific cargos and adaptor proteins such as Sequestosome-1/p62.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The completed autophagosome then fuses with a lysosome through the actions of multiple proteins, including SNAREs and UVRAG.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Following the fusion LC3 is retained on the vesicle's inner side and degraded along with the cargo, while the LC3 molecules attached to the outer side are cleaved off by Atg4 and recycled.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The contents of the autolysosome are subsequently degraded and their building blocks are released from the vesicle through the action of permeases.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Sirtuin 1 (SIRT1) stimulates autophagy by preventing acetylation of proteins (via deacetylation) required for autophagy as demonstrated in cultured cells and embryonic and neonatal tissues.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This function provides a link between sirtuin expression and the cellular response to limited nutrients due to caloric restriction.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy has roles in various cellular functions.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] One particular example is in yeasts, where the nutrient starvation induces a high level of autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This allows unneeded proteins to be degraded and the amino acids recycled for the synthesis of proteins that are essential for survival.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In higher eukaryotes, autophagy is induced in response to the nutrient depletion that occurs in animals at birth after severing off the trans-placental food supply, as well as that of nutrient starved cultured cells and tissues.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Mutant yeast cells that have a reduced autophagic capability rapidly perish in nutrition-deficient conditions.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Studies on the *apg* mutants suggest that autophagy via autophagic bodies is indispensable for protein degradation in the vacuoles under starvation conditions, and that at least 15 APG genes are involved in autophagy in yeast.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] A gene known as ATG7 has been implicated in nutrient-mediated autophagy, as mice studies have shown that starvation-induced autophagy was impaired in *atg7*-deficient mice.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Vesicular stomatitis virus is believed to be taken up by the autophagosome from the cytosol and translocated to the endosomes where detection takes place by a pattern recognition receptor called toll-like receptor 7, detecting single stranded RNA.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Following activation of the toll-like receptor, intracellular signaling cascades are initiated, leading to induction of interferon and other antiviral cytokines.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] A subset of viruses and bacteria subvert the autophagic pathway to promote their own replication.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Galectin-8 has recently been identified as an intracellular "danger receptor", able to initiate autophagy against intracellular pathogens.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] When galectin-8 binds to a damaged vacuole, it recruits an autophagy adaptor such as NDP52 leading to the formation of an autophagosome and bacterial degradation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy degrades damaged organelles, cell membranes and proteins, and insufficient autophagy is thought to be one of the main reasons for the accumulation of damaged cells and aging.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy and autophagy regulators are involved in response to lysosomal damage, often directed by galectins such as galectin-3 and galectin-8.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Repair of damaged DNA involves the recruitment of enzymes to the damaged site, but these enzymes must be removed upon completion of the repair process.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Topoisomerase I cleavage complex is employed in the processing of DNA damages (e.g.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] DNA-protein crosslinks) in vertebrates, and this complex is selectively degraded by autophagy, presumably after it is no longer needed.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] One of the mechanisms of programmed cell death (PCD) is associated with the appearance of autophagosomes and depends on autophagy proteins.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This form of cell death most likely corresponds to a process that has been morphologically defined as autophagic PCD.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] One question that constantly arises, however, is whether autophagic activity in dying cells is the cause of death or is actually an attempt to prevent it.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Morphological and histochemical studies have not so far proved a causative relationship between the autophagic process and cell death.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In fact, there have recently been strong arguments that autophagic activity in dying cells might actually be a survival mechanism.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Studies of the metamorphosis of insects have shown cells undergoing a form of PCD that appears distinct from other forms; these have been proposed as examples of autophagic cell death.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Recent pharmacological and biochemical studies have proposed that survival and lethal autophagy can be distinguished by the type and degree of regulatory signaling during stress particularly after viral infection.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Although promising, these findings have not been examined in non-viral systems.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Mammalian fetal oocytes face several challenges to survival throughout the stages of meiotic prophase I prior to primordial follicle assembly.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Each primordial follicle contains an immature primary oocyte.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Before oocytes are enclosed into a primordial follicle, deficiencies of nutrients or growth factors might activate protective autophagy, but this can turn into death of the oocytes if starvation is prolonged.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy is essential for basal homeostasis; it is also extremely important in maintaining muscle homeostasis during physical exercise.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy at the molecular level is only partially understood.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] A study of mice shows that autophagy is important for the ever-changing demands of their nutritional and energy needs, particularly through the metabolic pathways of protein catabolism.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Results showed that when compared to a control group, these mice illustrated a decrease in endurance and an altered glucose metabolism during acute exercise.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Another study demonstrated that skeletal muscle fibers of collagen VI in knockout mice showed signs of degeneration due to an insufficiency of autophagy which led to an accumulation of damaged mitochondria and excessive cell death.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Exercise-induced autophagy was unsuccessful however; but when autophagy was induced artificially post-exercise, the accumulation of damaged organelles in collagen VI deficient muscle fibres was prevented and cellular homeostasis was maintained.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Both studies demonstrate that autophagy induction may contribute to the beneficial metabolic effects of exercise and that it is essential in the maintaining of muscle homeostasis during exercise, particularly in collagen VI fibers.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Work at the Institute for Cell Biology, University of Bonn, showed that a certain type of autophagy, i.e. chaperone-assisted selective autophagy (CASA), is induced in contracting muscles and is required for maintaining the muscle sarcomere under mechanical tension.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The CASA chaperone complex recognizes mechanically damaged cytoskeleton components and directs these components through a ubiquitin-dependent autophagic sorting pathway to lysosomes for disposal.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This is necessary for maintaining muscle activity.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Because autophagy decreases with age and age is a major risk factor for osteoarthritis, the role of autophagy in the development of this disease is suggested.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Proteins involved in autophagy are reduced with age in both human and mouse articular cartilage.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Mechanical injury to cartilage explants in culture also reduced autophagy proteins.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy is constantly activated in normal cartilage but it is compromised with age and precedes cartilage cell death and structural damage.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Thus autophagy is involved in a normal protective process (chondroprotection) in the joint.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Cancer often occurs when several different pathways that regulate cell differentiation are disturbed.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy plays an important role in cancer – both in protecting against cancer as well as potentially contributing to the growth of cancer.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The role of autophagy in cancer is one that has been highly researched and reviewed.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] There is evidence that emphasizes the role of autophagy as both a tumor suppressor and a factor in tumor cell survival.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Recent research has shown, however, that autophagy is more likely to be used as a tumor suppressor according to several models.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Several experiments have been done with mice and varying Beclin1, a protein that regulates autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] When the Beclin1 gene was altered to be heterozygous (Beclin 1±), the mice were found to be tumor-prone.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] However, when Beclin1 was overexpressed, tumor development was inhibited.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In addition, full knockout of Beclin1 is embryonic lethal whereas knockout of Atg7 or Atg5 is not.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Necrosis and chronic inflammation also has been shown to be limited through autophagy which helps protect against the formation of tumor cells.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Colorectal cancer incidence is associated with a high-fat diet, and such a diet is linked to elevated levels of bile acids in the colon, particularly deoxycholic acid.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Deoxycholic acid induces autophagy in non-cancer colon epithelial cells and this induction of autophagy contributes to cell survival when cells are stressed.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Also autophagy is a survival pathway that is constitutively present in apoptosis-resistant colon cancer cells.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The constitutive activation of autophagy in colon cancer cells, is thus a colon cancer cell survival strategy that needs to be overcome in colon cancer therapy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Cells that undergo an extreme amount of stress experience cell death either through apoptosis or necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Prolonged autophagy activation leads to a high turnover rate of proteins and organelles.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] A high rate above the survival threshold may kill cancer cells with a high apoptotic threshold.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This technique can be utilized as a therapeutic cancer treatment.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Alternatively, autophagy has also been shown to play a large role in tumor cell survival.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] In cancerous cells, autophagy is used as a way to deal with stress on the cell.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Induction of autophagy by miRNA-4673, for example, is a pro-survival mechanism that improves the resistance of cancer cells to radiation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Once these autophagy related genes were inhibited, cell death was potentiated.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The increase in metabolic energy is offset by autophagy functions.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] These metabolic stresses include hypoxia, nutrient deprivation, and an increase in proliferation.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] These stresses activate autophagy in order to recycle ATP and maintain survival of the cancerous cells.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Autophagy has been shown to enable continued growth of tumor cells by maintaining cellular energy production.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] By inhibiting autophagy genes in these tumors cells, regression of the tumor and extended survival of the organs affected by the tumors were found.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Furthermore, inhibition of autophagy has also been shown to enhance the effectiveness of anticancer therapies.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] New developments in research have found that targeted autophagy may be a viable therapeutic solution in fighting cancer.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] As discussed above, autophagy plays both a role in tumor suppression and tumor cell survival.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Thus, the qualities of autophagy can be used as a strategy for cancer prevention.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The first strategy is to induce autophagy and enhance its tumor suppression attributes.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The second strategy is to inhibit autophagy and thus induce apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The first strategy has been tested by looking at dose-response anti-tumor effects during autophagy-induced therapies.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] These therapies have shown that autophagy increases in a dose-dependent manner.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This is directly related to the growth of cancer cells in a dose-dependent manner as well.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] These data support the development of therapies that will encourage autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Secondly, inhibiting the protein pathways directly known to induce autophagy may also serve as an anticancer therapy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The second strategy is based on the idea that autophagy is a protein degradation system used to maintain homeostasis and the findings that inhibition of autophagy often leads to apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Inhibition of autophagy is riskier as it may lead to cell survival instead of the desired cell death.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Negative regulators of autophagy, such as mTOR, cFLIP, EGFR, (GAPR-1), and Rubicon are orchestrated to function within different stages of the autophagy cascade.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] The end-products of autophagic digestion may also serve as a negative-feedback regulatory mechanism to stop prolonged activity.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Regulators of autophagy control regulators of inflammation, and vice versa.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Cells of vertebrate organisms normally activate inflammation to enhance the capacity of the immune system to clear infections and to initiate the processes that restore tissue structure and function.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] This renders cancer cells vulnerable to intervention on regulators of autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/autophagy] Excessive activity of the crinophagy form of autophagy in the insulin-producing beta cells of the pancreas could reduce the quantity of insulin available for secretion, leading to type 2 diabetes.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Members of the BCL-2 family regulate apoptosis in mammals, reptiles, amphibs, fish, and other phyla of metazoan life, with exception of nematodes and insects.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Their molecular structure and function, as well as their protein dynamics, are highly conserved over hundreds of millions of years in tissue forming life forms.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Bcl-2 family proteins have a general structure that consists of a hydrophobic α-helix surrounded by amphipathic α-helices.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Some members of the family have transmembrane domains at their c-terminus which primarily function to localize them to the mitochondrion.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Bcl-x(L) is 233 amino acyl residues (aas) long and exhibits a single very hydrophobic putative transmembrane α-helical segment (residues 210-226) when in the membrane.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Homologues of Bcl-x include the Bax (rat; 192 aas) and Bak (mouse; 208 aas) proteins, which also influence apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The high resolution structure of the monomeric soluble form of human Bcl-x(L) has been determined by both x-ray crystallography and NMR.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The structure consists of two central primarily hydrophobic α-helices surrounded by amphipathic helices.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The arrangement of the α-helices in Bcl-X(L) resembles that for diphtheria toxin and the colicins.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Diphtheria toxin forms a transmembrane pore and translocates the toxic catalytic domain into the animal cell cytoplasm.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The colicins similarly form pores in lipid bilayers.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Structural homology therefore suggests that Bcl-2 family members that contain the BH1 and BH2 domains (Bcl-X(L) Bcl-2 and Bax) function similarly.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The members of the Bcl-2 family share one or more of the four characteristic domains of homology entitled the Bcl-2 homology (BH) domains (named BH1, BH2, BH3 and BH4) (see figure).
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH domains are known to be crucial for function, as deletion of these domains via molecular cloning affects survival/apoptosis rates.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 proteins, such as Bcl-2 and Bcl-xL, conserve all four BH domains.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH domains also serve to subdivide the pro-apoptotic Bcl-2 proteins into those with several BH domains (e.g.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Bax and Bak) or those proteins that have only the BH3 domain (e.g.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] All proteins belonging to the Bcl-2 family contain either a BH1, BH2, BH3 or BH4 domain.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] All anti-apoptotic proteins contain BH1 and BH2 domains, some of them contain an additional N-terminal BH4 domain (Bcl-2, Bcl-x(L) and Bcl-w), which is also seen in some pro-apoptotic proteins like Bcl-x(S), Diva, Bok-L and Bok-S.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] On the other hand, all pro-apoptotic proteins contain a BH3 domain necessary for dimerization with other proteins of Bcl-2 family and crucial for their killing activity, some of them also contain BH1 and BH2 domains (Bax and Bak).
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH3 domain is also present in some anti-apoptotic protein, such as Bcl-2 or Bcl-x(L).
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The three functionally important Bcl-2 homology regions (BH1, BH2 and BH3) are in close spatial proximity.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] They form an elongated cleft that may provide the binding site for other Bcl-2 family members.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Regulated cell death (apoptosis) is induced by events such as growth factor withdrawal and toxins.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] It is controlled by regulators, which have either an inhibitory effect on programmed cell death (anti-apoptotic) or block the protective effect of inhibitors (pro-apoptotic).
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Many viruses have found a way of countering defensive apoptosis by encoding their own anti-apoptosis genes preventing their target-cells from dying too soon.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Bcl-x is a dominant regulator of programmed cell death in mammalian cells.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The long form (Bcl-x(L), displays cell death repressor activity, but the short isoform (Bcl-x(S)) and the β-isoform (Bcl-xβ) promote cell death.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Bcl-x(L), Bcl-x(S) and Bcl-xβ are three isoforms derived by alternative RNA splicing.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] There are a number of theories concerning how the Bcl-2 gene family exert their pro- or anti-apoptotic effect.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] An important one states that this is achieved by activation or inactivation of an inner mitochondrial permeability transition pore, which is involved in the regulation of matrix Ca2+, pH, and voltage.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] It is also thought that some Bcl-2 family proteins can induce (pro-apoptotic members) or inhibit (anti-apoptotic members) the release of cytochrome c into the cytosol which, once there, activates caspase-9 and caspase-3, leading to apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Although Zamzami et al. suggest that the release of cytochrome c is indirectly mediated by the PT pore on the inner mitochondrial membrane, strong evidence suggest an earlier implication of the MAC pore on the outer membrane.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Another theory suggests that Rho proteins play a role in Bcl-2, Mcl-1 and Bid activation.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Rho inhibition reduces the expression of anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 and Mcl-1 proteins and increases protein levels of pro-apoptotic Bid but had no effect on Bax or FLIP levels.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Rho inhibition induces caspase-9 and caspase-3-dependent apoptosis of cultured human endothelial cells.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] These proteins are localized to the outer mitochondrial membrane of the animal cell where they are thought to form a complex with the voltage-dependent anion channel porin (VDAC).
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Interaction of Bcl-2 with VDAC1 or with peptides derived from VDAC3 protects against cell death by inhibiting cytochrome c release.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] A direct interaction of Bcl-2 with bilayer-reconstituted purified VDAC was demonstrated, with Bcl-2 decreasing channel conductance.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Within the mitochondria are apoptogenic factors (cytochrome c, Smac/Diablo homolog, Omi) that if released activate the executioners of apoptosis, the caspases.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Depending on their function, once activated, Bcl-2 proteins either promote the release of these factors, or keep them sequestered in the mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Whereas the activated pro-apoptotic Bak and/or Bax would form MAC and mediate the release of cytochrome c, the anti-apoptotic Bcl-2 would block it, possibly through inhibition of Bax and/or Bak.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Proteins of the Bcl-2 family are also present in the perinuclear envelope and are widely distributed in many body tissues.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Their ability to form oligomeric pores in artificial lipid bilayers has been documented but the physiological significance of pore formation is not clear.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Each of these proteins has distinctive properties, including some degree of ion selectivity.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH3-only subset of the Bcl-2 family of proteins contain only a single BH3-domain.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH3-only members play a key role in promoting apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] The BH3-only family members are Bim, Bid, BAD and others.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Various apoptotic stimuli induce expression and/or activation of specific BH3-only family members, which translocate to the mitochondria and initiate Bax/Bak-dependent apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/bcl-2-family] Proteins that are known to contain these domains include vertebrate Bcl-2 (alpha and beta isoforms) and Bcl-x (isoforms Bcl-x(L).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The role of these enzymes in programmed cell death was first identified in 1993, with their functions in apoptosis well characterised.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This is a form of programmed cell death, occurring widely during development, and throughout life to maintain cell homeostasis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Activation of caspases ensures that the cellular components are degraded in a controlled manner, carrying out cell death with minimal effect on surrounding tissues.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspases have other identified roles in programmed cell death such as pyroptosis, necroptosis and PANoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] These forms of cell death are important for protecting an organism from stress signals and pathogenic attack.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspases also have a role in inflammation, whereby it directly processes pro-inflammatory cytokines such as pro-IL1β.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] These are signalling molecules that allow recruitment of immune cells to an infected cell or tissue.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] There are other identified roles of caspases such as cell proliferation, tumor suppression, cell differentiation, neural development and axon guidance and ageing.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Most caspases play a role in programmed cell death.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] These are summarized in the table below.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The enzymes are sub classified into three types: Initiator, Executioner and Inflammatory.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Note that in addition to apoptosis, caspase-8 is also required for the inhibition of another form of programmed cell death called necroptosis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspase-14 plays a role in epithelial cell keratinocyte differentiation and can form an epidermal barrier that protects against dehydration and UVB radiation.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspases are synthesised as inactive zymogens (pro-caspases) that are only activated following an appropriate stimulus.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This post-translational level of control allows rapid and tight regulation of the enzyme.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Activation involves dimerization and often oligomerisation of pro-caspases, followed by cleavage into a small subunit and large subunit.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The large and small subunit associate with each other to form an active heterodimer caspase.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The active enzyme often exists as a heterotetramer in the biological environment, where a pro-caspase dimer is cleaved together to form a heterotetramer.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The activation of initiator caspases and inflammatory caspases is initiated by dimerisation, which is facilitated by binding to adaptor proteins via protein–protein interaction motifs that are collectively referred to as death folds.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The death folds are located in a structural domain of the caspases known as the pro-domain, which is larger in those caspases that contain death folds than in those that do not.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The pro-domain of the intrinsic initiator caspases and the inflammatory caspases contains a single death fold known as caspase recruitment domain (CARD), while the pro-domain of the extrinsic initiator caspases contains two death folds known as death effector domains (DED).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Once appropriately dimerised, the Caspases cleave at inter domain linker regions, forming a large and small subunit.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This cleavage allows the active-site loops to take up a conformation favourable for enzymatic activity.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Apoptosis is a form of programmed cell death where the cell undergoes morphological changes, to minimize its effect on surrounding cells to avoid inducing an immune response.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The cell shrinks and condenses - the cytoskeleton will collapse, and the nuclear envelope disassembles the DNA fragments up.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This results in the cell forming self-enclosed bodies called 'blebs', to avoid release of cellular components into the extracellular medium.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Additionally, the cell membrane phospholipid content is altered, which makes the dying cell more susceptible to phagocytic attack and removal.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Once initiator caspases are activated, they produce a chain reaction, activating several other executioner caspases.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Executioner caspases degrade over 600 cellular components in order to induce the morphological changes for apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] *Extrinsic apoptotic pathway:* The caspase cascade is also activated by extracellular ligands, via cell surface Death Receptors.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This is done by the formation of a multiprotein Death Inducing Signalling Complex (DISC) that recruits and activates a pro-caspase.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] For example, the Fas Ligand binds the FasR receptor at the receptor's extracellular surface; this activates the death domains at the cytoplasmic tail of the receptor.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The adaptor protein FADD will recruit (by a Death domain-Death domain interaction) pro-Caspase 8 via the DED domain.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Pyroptosis is a form of programmed cell death that inherently induces an immune response.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] It is morphologically distinct from other types of cell death – cells swell up, rupture and release pro-inflammatory cellular contents.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This is done in response to a range of stimuli including microbial infections as well as heart attacks (myocardial infarctions).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspase-1, Caspase-4 and Caspase-5 in humans, and Caspase-1 and Caspase-11 in mice play important roles in inducing cell death by pyroptosis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This limits the life and proliferation time of intracellular and extracellular pathogens.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspase-1 activation is mediated by a repertoire of proteins, allowing detection of a range of pathogenic ligands.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Some mediators of Caspase-1 activation are: NOD-like Leucine Rich Repeats (NLRs), AIM2-Like Receptors (ALRs), Pyrin and IFI16.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] These proteins allow caspase-1 activation by forming a multiprotein activating complex called Inflammasomes.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] For example, a NOD Like Leucine Rich Repeat NLRP3 will sense an efflux of potassium ions from the cell.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This cellular ion imbalance leads to oligomerisation of NLRP3 molecules to form a multiprotein complex called the NLRP3 inflammasome.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The pro-caspase-1 is brought into close proximity with other pro-caspase molecule in order to dimerise and undergo auto-proteolytic cleavage.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] These caspases have the ability to induce direct pyroptosis when lipopolysaccharide (LPS) molecules (found in the cell wall of gram negative bacteria) are found in the cytoplasm of the host cell.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] For example, Caspase 4 acts as a receptor and is proteolytically activated, without the need of an inflammasome complex or Caspase-1 activation.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Inflammation is a protective attempt by an organism to restore a homeostatic state, following disruption from harmful stimulus, such as tissue damage or bacterial infection.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspase-1, Caspase-4, Caspase-5 and Caspase-11 are considered 'Inflammatory Caspases'.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Robert Horvitz initially established the importance of caspases in apoptosis and found that the *ced-3* gene is required for the cell death that took place during the development of the nematode *C. elegans*.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Horvitz and his colleague Junying Yuan found in 1993 that the protein encoded by the ced-3 gene is cysteine protease with similar properties to the mammalian interleukin-1-beta converting enzyme (ICE) (now known as caspase 1).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] At the time, ICE was the only known caspase.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Other mammalian caspases were subsequently identified, in addition to caspases in organisms such as fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Researchers decided upon the nomenclature of the caspase in 1996.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] In many instances, a particular caspase had been identified simultaneously by more than one laboratory; each would then give the protein a different name.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] For example, caspase 3 was variously known as CPP32, apopain and Yama.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Caspases, therefore, were numbered in the order in which they were identified.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] ICE was, therefore, renamed as caspase 1.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] ICE was the first mammalian caspase to be characterised because of its similarity to the nematode death gene ced-3, but it appears that the principal role of this enzyme is to mediate inflammation rather than cell death.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] In animals apoptosis is induced by caspases and in fungi and plants, apoptosis is induced by arginine and lysine-specific caspase-like proteases called metacaspases.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Homology searches revealed a close homology between caspases and the caspase-like proteins of *Reticulomyxa* (a unicellular organism).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] The phylogenetic study indicates that divergence of caspase and metacaspase sequences occurred before the divergence of eukaryotes.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Detection of executioner caspase activity frequently utilizes the tetrapeptide DEVD, which corresponds to the preferred cleavage motif for caspase‑3 and caspase‑7.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] DEVD is a short peptide sequence made up of four amino acids: **D** – Aspartic acid (Asp); **E** – Glutamic acid (Glu); **V** – Valine (Val); **D** – Aspartic acid (Asp).
[src:apoptosis/caspase] In fluorometric assays, substrates such as DEVD‑AMC or DEVD‑AFC release a fluorescent moiety upon caspase-mediated cleavage; the fluorescence intensity serves as a direct readout of enzymatic activity.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] Chromogenic alternatives like DEVD‑pNA allow similar spectrophotometric measurement.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] More sophisticated approaches employ genetically encoded biosensors containing a DEVD linker, which restore fluorescence only after cleavage by active caspases, enabling real-time, live-cell monitoring of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] A dual-fluorescent reporter system combining a DEVD-containing ZipGFP biosensor with constitutive mCherry expression has been developed.
[src:apoptosis/caspase] This platform permits dynamic tracking of caspase‑3/‑7 activation and apoptosis in both 2D and 3D culture systems, including spheroids and organoids, and can be integrated with calreticulin exposure assays to differentiate immunogenic forms of cell death.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The **cytochrome complex**, or **cyt c**, is a small hemeprotein found loosely associated with the inner membrane of the mitochondrion, where it plays a critical role in cellular respiration.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] It transfers electrons between Complexes III (Coenzyme Q – Cyt c reductase) and IV (Cyt c oxidase).
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c is highly water-soluble, unlike other cytochromes.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] It is capable of undergoing oxidation and reduction as its iron atom converts between the ferrous and ferric forms, but does not bind oxygen.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] It also plays a major role in cell apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In humans, cytochrome c is encoded by the *CYCS* gene.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c is a highly conserved protein across the spectrum of eukaryotic species, found in plants, animals, fungi, and many unicellular organisms.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This, along with its small size (molecular weight about 12,000 daltons), makes it useful in studies of cladistics.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c has been studied for the glimpse it gives into evolutionary biology.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c has a primary structure consisting of a chain of about 100 amino acids.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Many higher-order organisms possess a chain of 104 amino acids.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The sequence of cytochrome c in humans is identical to that of chimpanzees (our closest relatives), but differs from that of horses.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c has an amino acid sequence that is highly conserved in eukaryotes, varying by only a few residues.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In more than thirty species tested in one study, 34 of the 104 amino acids were conserved (identical at their characteristic position).
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] For example, human cytochrome oxidase reacted with wheat cytochrome *c*, *in vitro*; which held true for all pairs of species tested.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In addition, the redox potential of +0.25 volts is the same in all cytochrome *c* molecules studied.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c belongs to class I of the c-type cytochrome family and contains a characteristic CXXCH (cysteine-any-any-cysteine-histidine) amino acid motif that binds heme.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This motif is located towards the N-terminus of the peptide chain and contains a histidine as the 5th ligand of the heme iron.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The 6th ligand is provided by a methionine residue found towards the C-terminus.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The protein backbone is folded into five α-helices that are numbered α1-α5 from N-terminus to C-terminus.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Helices α3, α4 and α5 are referred to as 50s, 60s and 70s helices, respectively, when referring to mitochondrial cytochrome c.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] While most heme proteins are attached to the prosthetic group through iron ion ligation and tertiary interactions, the heme group of cytochrome c makes thioether bonds with two cysteine side chains of the protein.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] One of the main properties of heme c, which allows cytochrome c to have variety of functions, is its ability to have different reduction potentials in nature.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This property determines the kinetics and thermodynamics of an electron transfer reaction.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The dipole moment has an important role in orienting proteins to the proper directions and enhancing their abilities to bind to other molecules.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The dipole moment of cytochrome c results from a cluster of negatively charged amino acid side chains at the "back" of the enzyme.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Despite variations in the number of bound heme groups and variations in sequence, the dipole moment of vertebrate cytochromes c is remarkably conserved.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] For example, vertebrate cytochromes c all have a dipole moment of approximately 320 debye while cytochromes c of plants and insects have a dipole moment of approximately 340 debye.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c is an essential component of the respiratory electron transport chain in mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The heme group of cytochrome c accepts electrons from the bc1 Complex III and transports them to Complex IV, while it transfers energy in the opposite direction.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c can also catalyze several redox reactions such as hydroxylation and aromatic oxidation, and shows peroxidase activity by oxidation of various electron donors such as 2,2-azino-*bis*(3-ethylbenzthiazoline-6-sulfonic acid) (ABTS), 2-keto-4-thiomethyl butyric acid and 4-aminoantipyrine.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] A bacterial cytochrome *c* functions as a nitrite reductase.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c was also discovered in 1996 by Xiaodong Wang to have an intermediate role in apoptosis, a controlled form of cell death used to kill cells in the process of development or in response to infection or DNA damage.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c binds to cardiolipin in the inner mitochondrial membrane, thus anchoring its presence and keeping it from releasing out of the mitochondria and initiating apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] While the initial attraction between cardiolipin and cytochrome c is electrostatic due to the extreme positive charge on cytochrome c, the final interaction is hydrophobic, where a hydrophobic tail from cardiolipin inserts itself into the hydrophobic portion of cytochrome c.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] During the early phase of apoptosis, mitochondrial ROS production is stimulated, and cardiolipin is oxidized by a peroxidase function of the cardiolipin–cytochrome c complex.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The hemoprotein is then detached from the mitochondrial inner membrane and can be extruded into the soluble cytoplasm through pores in the outer membrane.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The sustained elevation in calcium levels precedes cyt *c* release from the mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The release of small amounts of cyt *c* leads to an interaction with the IP3 receptor (IP3R) on the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), causing ER calcium release.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The overall increase in calcium triggers a massive release of cyt *c*, which then acts in the positive feedback loop to maintain ER calcium release through the IP3Rs.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This explains how the ER calcium release can reach cytotoxic levels.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This release of cytochrome c in turn activates caspase 9, a cysteine protease.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Caspase 9 can then go on to activate caspase 3 and caspase 7, which destroy the cell from within.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] One of the ways cell apoptosis is activated is by release of cytochrome c from the mitochondria into cytosol.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] A study has shown that cells are able to protect themselves from apoptosis by blocking the release of cytochrome c using Bcl-xL.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Another way that cells can control apoptosis is by phosphorylation of Tyr48, which turns cytochrome c into an anti-apoptotic switch.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In addition to its well-known roles in the electron transport chain and cell apoptosis, according to a 2008 study cytochrome c can also act as an antioxidative enzyme in the mitochondria; it does so by removing superoxide (O−2) and hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) from mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Therefore, not only is cytochrome c required in the mitochondria for cellular respiration, but it is also needed in the mitochondria to limit the production of O−2 and H2O2.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c is widely believed to be localised solely in the mitochondrial intermembrane space under normal physiological conditions.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The release of cytochrome c from mitochondria to the cytosol, where it activates the caspase family of proteases, is believed to be the primary trigger leading to the onset of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Measuring the amount of cytochrome c leaking from mitochondria to cytosol, and out of the cell to culture medium, is a sensitive method to monitor the degree of apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] However, detailed immuno-electronmicroscopic studies with rat tissues sections employing cytochrome c specific antibodies provide compelling evidence that cytochrome c under normal cellular conditions is also present at extramitochondrial locations.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In pancreatic acinar cells and the anterior pituitary, strong and specific presence of cytochrome c was detected in zymogen granules and in growth hormone granules, respectively.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In the pancreas, cytochrome c was also found in condensing vacuoles and in the acinar lumen.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] The extramitochondrial localisation of cytochrome c was shown to be specific as it was completely abolished upon adsorption of the primary antibody with purified cytochrome c.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Besides cytochrome c, extramitochondrial localisation has also been observed for large numbers of other proteins including those encoded by mitochondrial DNA.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This raises the possibility of the existence of yet-unidentified specific mechanisms for protein translocation from mitochondria to other cellular destinations.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c has been used to detect peroxide production in biological systems.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] As superoxide is produced, the number of oxidised cytochrome c3+ increases, and reduced cytochrome c2+ decreases.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] However, superoxide is often produced with nitric oxide.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] In the presence of nitric oxide, the reduction of cytochrome c3+ is inhibited.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This leads to the oxidisation of cytochrome c2+ to cytochrome c3+ by peroxynitrous acid, an intermediate made through the reaction of nitric oxide and superoxide.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Presence of peroxynitrite or H2O2 and nitrogen dioxide NO2 in the mitochondria can be lethal since they nitrate tyrosine residues of cytochrome c, which leads to disruption of cytochrome c's function as an electron carrier in the electron transport chain.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c has also been widely studied as an enzyme with peroxidase-like activity.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Cytochrome c was conjugated to charged polymer to test its peroxidase-like activity.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] Authors observed unique catalytic activity behavior upon encapsulating enzyme inside a protein-cage, which was different from enzyme in solution.
[src:apoptosis/cytochrome-c] This was attributed to local microenvironment provided by Dps nanocage's interior cavity which is different than bulk.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Cellular death due to necrosis does not follow the apoptotic signal transduction pathway, but rather various receptors are activated and result in the loss of cell membrane integrity and an uncontrolled release of products of cell death into the extracellular space.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] This initiates an inflammatory response in the surrounding tissue, which attracts leukocytes and nearby phagocytes which eliminate the dead cells by phagocytosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] However, microbial damaging substances released by leukocytes would create collateral damage to surrounding tissues.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] This excess collateral damage inhibits the healing process.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Thus, untreated necrosis results in a build-up of decomposing dead tissue and cell debris at or near the site of the cell death.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] For this reason, it is often necessary to remove necrotic tissue surgically, a procedure known as *debridement*.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Structural signs that indicate irreversible cell injury and the progression of necrosis include dense clumping and progressive disruption of genetic material, and disruption to membranes of cells and organelles.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Liquefactive necrosis (or colliquative necrosis), in contrast to coagulative necrosis, is characterized by the digestion of dead cells to form a viscous liquid mass.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] This is typical of bacterial, or sometimes fungal, infections because of their ability to stimulate an inflammatory response.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The necrotic liquid mass is frequently creamy yellow due to the presence of dead leukocytes and is commonly known as pus.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Hypoxic infarcts in the brain presents as this type of necrosis, because the brain contains little connective tissue but high amounts of digestive enzymes and lipids, and cells therefore can be readily digested by their own enzymes.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Gangrenous necrosis can be considered a type of coagulative necrosis that resembles mummified tissue.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] It is characteristic of ischemia of lower limb and the gastrointestinal tracts.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Both dry gangrene and gas gangrene can lead to this type of necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] If superimposed infection of dead tissues occurs, then liquefactive necrosis ensues (wet gangrene).
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Caseous necrosis can be considered a combination of coagulative and liquefactive necrosis, typically caused by mycobacteria (e.g. tuberculosis), fungi and some foreign substances.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The necrotic tissue appears as white and friable, like clumped cheese.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Dead cells disintegrate but are not completely digested, leaving granular particles.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Microscopic examination shows amorphous granular debris enclosed within a distinctive inflammatory border.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Some granulomas contain this pattern of necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Fat necrosis is specialized necrosis of fat tissue, resulting from the action of activated lipases on fatty tissues such as the pancreas.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In the pancreas it leads to acute pancreatitis, a condition where the pancreatic enzymes leak out into the peritoneal cavity, and liquefy the membrane by splitting the triglyceride esters into fatty acids through fat saponification.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Calcium, magnesium or sodium may bind to these lesions to produce a chalky-white substance.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The calcium deposits are microscopically distinctive and may be large enough to be visible on radiographic examinations.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] To the naked eye, calcium deposits appear as gritty white flecks.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Fibrinoid necrosis is a special form of necrosis usually caused by immune-mediated vascular damage.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] It is marked by complexes of antigen and antibodies, referred to as immune complexes deposited within arterial walls together with fibrin.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Myonecrosis is the death of individual muscle fibres due to injury, hypoxia, or infection.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Common causes include spontaneous diabetic myonecrosis (a.k.a. diabetic muscle infarction) and clostridial myonecrosis (a.k.a. gas gangrene).
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In the United States, only spider bites from the brown recluse spider (genus Loxosceles) reliably progress to necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In other countries, spiders of the same genus, such as the Chilean recluse in South America, are also known to cause necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Claims that yellow sac spiders and hobo spiders possess necrotic venom have not been substantiated.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In blind mole rats (genus *Spalax*), the process of necrosis replaces the role of the systematic apoptosis normally used in many organisms.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Low oxygen conditions, such as those common in blind mole rats' burrows, usually cause cells to undergo apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In adaptation to higher tendency of cell death, blind mole rats evolved a mutation in the tumor suppressor protein p53 (which is also used in humans) to prevent cells from undergoing apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Human cancer patients have similar mutations, and blind mole rats were thought to be more susceptible to cancer because their cells cannot undergo apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In this case, the interferon-beta triggers cells to undergo necrosis, and this mechanism also kills cancer cells in blind mole rats.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Because of tumor suppression mechanisms such as this, blind mole rats and other spalacids are resistant to cancer.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Necrosis may occur due to external or internal factors.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] External factors may involve mechanical trauma (physical damage to the body which causes cellular breakdown), electric shock, damage to blood vessels (which may disrupt blood supply to associated tissue), and ischemia.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Thermal effects (extremely high or low temperature) can often result in necrosis due to the disruption of cells, especially in bone cells.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Necrosis can also result from chemical trauma, with alkaline and acidic compounds causing liquefactive and coagulative necrosis, respectively, in affected tissues.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The severity of such cases varies significantly based on multiple factors, including the compound concentration, type of tissue affected, and the extent of chemical exposure.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In frostbite, crystals form, increasing the pressure of remaining tissue and fluid causing the cells to burst.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Under extreme conditions tissues and cells may die through an unregulated process of membrane and cytosol destruction.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Internal factors causing necrosis include: trophoneurotic disorders (diseases that occur due to defective nerve action in a part of an organ which results in failure of nutrition); injury and paralysis of nerve cells.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Pancreatic enzymes (lipases) are the major cause of fat necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Necrosis can be activated by components of the immune system, such as the complement system; bacterial toxins; activated natural killer cells; and peritoneal macrophages.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Pathogen-induced necrosis programs in cells with immunological barriers (intestinal mucosa) may alleviate invasion of pathogens through surfaces affected by inflammation.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Toxins and pathogens may cause necrosis; toxins such as snake venoms may inhibit enzymes and cause cell death.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Pathological conditions are characterized by inadequate secretion of cytokines.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Nitric oxide (NO) and reactive oxygen species (ROS) are also accompanied by intense necrotic death of cells.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] A classic example of a necrotic condition is ischemia which leads to a drastic depletion of oxygen, glucose, and other trophic factors and induces massive necrotic death of endothelial cells and non-proliferating cells of surrounding tissues (neurons, cardiomyocytes, renal cells, etc.).
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Recent cytological data indicates that necrotic death occurs not only during pathological events but it is also a component of some physiological process.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Until recently, necrosis was thought to be an unregulated process.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] However, there are two broad pathways in which necrosis may occur in an organism.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The first of these two pathways initially involves oncosis, where swelling of the cells occurs.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Affected cells then proceed to blebbing, and this is followed by pyknosis, in which nuclear shrinkage transpires.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In the final step of this pathway cell nuclei are dissolved into the cytoplasm, which is referred to as karyolysis.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The second pathway is a secondary form of necrosis that is shown to occur after apoptosis and budding.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] In these cellular changes of necrosis, the nucleus breaks into fragments (known as karyorrhexis).
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] On a larger histologic scale, **pseudopalisades** (false palisades) are hypercellular zones that typically surround necrotic tissue.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Pseudopalisading necrosis indicates an aggressive tumor.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] There are many causes of necrosis, and as such treatment is based upon how the necrosis came about.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Treatment of necrosis typically involves two distinct processes: Usually, the underlying cause of the necrosis must be treated before the dead tissue itself can be dealt with.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Even after the initial cause of the necrosis has been halted, the necrotic tissue will remain in the body.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] The body's immune response to apoptosis, which involves the automatic breaking down and recycling of cellular material, is not triggered by necrotic cell death due to the apoptotic pathway being disabled.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] If calcium is deficient, pectin cannot be synthesized, and therefore the cell walls cannot be bonded and thus an impediment of the meristems.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] This will lead to necrosis of stem and root tips and leaf edges.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] For example, necrosis of tissue can occur in *Arabidopsis thaliana* due to plant pathogens.
[src:apoptosis/necrosis] Cacti such as the Saguaro and Cardon in the Sonoran Desert experience necrotic patch formation regularly; a species of Dipterans called Drosophila *mettleri* has developed a P450 detoxification system to enable it to use the exudates released in these patches to both nest and feed larvae.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Apoptosis and autophagy are both forms of programmed cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Necrosis is the death of a cell caused by external factors such as trauma or infection and occurs in several different forms.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Necrosis was long seen as a non-physiological process that occurs as a result of infection or injury, but in the 2000s, a form of programmed necrosis, called necroptosis, was recognized as an alternative form of programmed cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is hypothesized that necroptosis can serve as a cell-death backup to apoptosis when the apoptosis signaling is blocked by endogenous or exogenous factors such as viruses or mutations.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Most recently, other types of regulated necrosis have been discovered as well, which share several signaling events with necroptosis and apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The concept of "programmed cell-death" was used by Lockshin & Williams in 1964 in relation to insect tissue development, around eight years before "apoptosis" was coined.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The term PCD has, however, been a source of confusion and Durand and Ramsey have developed the concept by providing mechanistic and evolutionary definitions.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] PCD has become the general terms that refers to all the different types of cell death that have a genetic component.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The first insight into the mechanism came from studying BCL2, the product of a putative oncogene activated by chromosome translocations often found in follicular lymphoma.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Unlike other cancer genes, which promote cancer by stimulating cell proliferation, BCL2 promoted cancer by stopping lymphoma cells from being able to kill themselves.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] PCD has been the subject of increasing attention and research efforts.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This trend has been highlighted with the award of the 2002 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine to Sydney Brenner (United Kingdom), H.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Apoptosis is the process of programmed cell death (PCD) that may occur in multicellular organisms.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Biochemical events lead to characteristic cell changes (morphology) and death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] These changes include blebbing, cell shrinkage, nuclear fragmentation, chromatin condensation, and chromosomal DNA fragmentation.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is now thought that -- in a developmental context -- cells are induced to positively commit suicide whilst in a homeostatic context; the absence of certain survival factors may provide the impetus for suicide.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There appears to be some variation in the morphology and indeed the biochemistry of these suicide pathways; some treading the path of "apoptosis", others following a more generalized pathway to deletion, but both usually being genetically and synthetically motivated.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There is some evidence that certain symptoms of "apoptosis" such as endonuclease activation can be spuriously induced without engaging a genetic cascade, however, presumably true apoptosis and programmed cell death must be genetically mediated.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is also becoming clear that mitosis and apoptosis are toggled or linked in some way and that the balance achieved depends on signals received from appropriate growth or survival factors.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There are two different potential pathways that may be followed when apoptosis is needed.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There is the extrinsic pathway and the intrinsic pathway.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Both pathways involve the use of caspases - crucial to cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The extrinsic pathway involves specific receptor ligand interaction.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Either the FAS ligand binds to the FAS receptor or the TNF-alpha ligand can bind to the TNF receptor.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In both situations there is the activation of initiator caspase.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The extrinsic pathway can be activated in two ways.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The first way is through fast ligand TNF-alpha binding or through a cytotoxic T-cell.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The cytotoxic T-cell can attach itself to a membrane, facilitating the release of granzyme B.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Granzyme B perforates the target cell membrane and in turn allows the release of perforin.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Finally, perforin creates a pore in the membrane, and releases the caspases which leads to the activation of caspase 3.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This initiator caspase may cause the cleaving of inactive caspase 3, causing it to become cleaved caspase 3.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This is the final molecule needed to trigger cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The intrinsic pathway is caused by cell damage such as DNA damage or UV exposure.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This pathway takes place in the mitochondria and is mediated by sensors called Bcl sensors, and two proteins called BAX and BAK.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] These proteins are found in a majority of higher mammals as they are able to pierce the mitochondrial outer membrane -- making them an integral part of mediating cell death by apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] They do this by orchestrating the formation of pores within the membrane -- essential to the release of cytochrome c.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] However, cytochrome c is only released if the mitochondrial membrane is compromised.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Once cytochrome c is detected, the apoptosome complex is formed.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This complex activates the executioner caspase which causes cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This killing of the cells may be essential as it prevents cellular overgrowth which can result in disease such as cancer.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There are another two proteins worth mentioning that inhibit the release of cytochrome c in the mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Bcl-2 and Bcl-xl are anti-apoptotic and therefore prevent cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] There is a potential mutation that can occur in that causes the overactivity of Bcl-2.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is the translocation between chromosomes 14 and 18.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This over activity can result in the development of follicular lymphoma.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Macroautophagy, often referred to as autophagy, is a catabolic process that results in the autophagosomal-lysosomal degradation of bulk cytoplasmic contents, abnormal protein aggregates, and excess or damaged organelles.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Autophagy is generally activated by conditions of nutrient deprivation but has also been associated with physiological as well as pathological processes such as development, differentiation, neurodegenerative diseases, stress, infection and cancer.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] A critical regulator of autophagy induction is the kinase mTOR, which when activated, suppresses autophagy and when not activated promotes it.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Three related serine/threonine kinases, UNC-51-like kinase -1, -2, and -3 (ULK1, ULK2, UKL3), which play a similar role as the yeast Atg1, act downstream of the mTOR complex.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] ULK1 and ULK2 form a large complex with the mammalian homolog of an autophagy-related (Atg) gene product (mAtg13) and the scaffold protein FIP200.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Class III PI3K complex, containing hVps34, Beclin-1, p150 and Atg14-like protein or ultraviolet irradiation resistance-associated gene (UVRAG), is required for the induction of autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The ATG genes control the autophagosome formation through ATG12-ATG5 and LC3-II (ATG8-II) complexes.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] ATG12 is conjugated to ATG5 in a ubiquitin-like reaction that requires ATG7 and ATG10.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The Atg12–Atg5 conjugate then interacts non-covalently with ATG16 to form a large complex.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] LC3/ATG8 is cleaved at its C terminus by ATG4 protease to generate the cytosolic LC3-I.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] LC3-I is conjugated to phosphatidylethanolamine (PE) also in a ubiquitin-like reaction that requires Atg7 and Atg3.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The lipidated form of LC3, known as LC3-II, is attached to the autophagosome membrane.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Autophagy and apoptosis are connected both positively and negatively, and extensive crosstalk exists between the two.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] During nutrient deficiency, autophagy functions as a pro-survival mechanism, however, excessive autophagy may lead to cell death, a process morphologically distinct from apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Several pro-apoptotic signals, such as TNF, TRAIL, and FADD, also induce autophagy.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Additionally, Bcl-2 inhibits Beclin-1-dependent autophagy, thereby functioning both as a pro-survival and as an anti-autophagic regulator.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Besides the above two types of PCD, other pathways have been discovered.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Called "non-apoptotic programmed cell-death" (or "caspase-independent programmed cell-death" or "necroptosis"), these alternative routes to death are as efficient as apoptosis and can function as either backup mechanisms or the main type of PCD.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Other forms of programmed cell death include anoikis, almost identical to apoptosis except in its induction; cornification, a form of cell death exclusive to the epidermis; excitotoxicity; ferroptosis, an iron-dependent form of cell death and Wallerian degeneration.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Necroptosis is a programmed form of necrosis, or inflammatory cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Conventionally, necrosis is associated with unprogrammed cell death resulting from cellular damage or infiltration by pathogens, in contrast to orderly, programmed cell death via apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Nemosis is another programmed form of necrosis that takes place in fibroblasts.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Eryptosis is a form of suicidal erythrocyte death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Aponecrosis is a hybrid of apoptosis and necrosis and refers to an incomplete apoptotic process that is completed by necrosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] NETosis is the process of cell-death generated by neutrophils, resulting in NETs.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Paraptosis is another type of nonapoptotic cell death that is mediated by MAPK through the activation of IGF-1.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It's characterized by the intracellular formation of vacuoles and swelling of mitochondria.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Pyroptosis, an inflammatory type of cell death, is uniquely mediated by caspase 1, an enzyme not involved in apoptosis, in response to infection by certain microorganisms.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Plant cells undergo particular processes of PCD similar to autophagic cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] However, some common features of PCD are highly conserved in both plants and metazoa.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] An atrophic factor is a force that causes a cell to die.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Only natural forces on the cell are considered to be atrophic factors, whereas, for example, agents of mechanical or chemical abuse or lysis of the cell are considered not to be atrophic factors.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The initial expansion of the developing nervous system is counterbalanced by the removal of neurons and their processes.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] During the development of the nervous system almost 50% of developing neurons are naturally removed by programmed cell death (PCD).
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] PCD in the nervous system was first recognized in 1896 by John Beard.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Since then several theories were proposed to understand its biological significance during neural development.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] PCD in the developing nervous system has been observed in proliferating as well as post-mitotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] One theory suggests that PCD is an adaptive mechanism to regulate the number of progenitor cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In humans, PCD in progenitor cells starts at gestational week 7 and remains until the first trimester.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This process of cell death has been identified in the germinal areas of the cerebral cortex, cerebellum, thalamus, brainstem, and spinal cord among other regions.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] At gestational weeks 19–23, PCD is observed in post-mitotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The prevailing theory explaining this observation is the neurotrophic theory which states that PCD is required to optimize the connection between neurons and their afferent inputs and efferent targets.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Another theory proposes that developmental PCD in the nervous system occurs in order to correct for errors in neurons that have migrated ectopically, innervated incorrect targets, or have axons that have gone awry during path finding.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is possible that PCD during the development of the nervous system serves different functions determined by the developmental stage, cell type, and even species.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The neurotrophic theory is the leading hypothesis used to explain the role of programmed cell death in the developing nervous system.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It postulates that in order to ensure optimal innervation of targets, a surplus of neurons is first produced which then compete for limited quantities of protective neurotrophic factors and only a fraction survive while others die by programmed cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Furthermore, the theory states that predetermined factors regulate the amount of neurons that survive and the size of the innervating neuronal population directly correlates to the influence of their target field.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The underlying idea that target cells secrete attractive or inducing factors and that their growth cones have a chemotactic sensitivity was first put forth by Santiago Ramon y Cajal in 1892.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Cajal presented the idea as an explanation for the "intelligent force" axons appear to take when finding their target but admitted that he had no empirical data.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The theory gained more attraction when experimental manipulation of axon targets yielded death of all innervating neurons.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This developed the concept of target derived regulation which became the main tenet in the neurotrophic theory.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Experiments that further supported this theory led to the identification of the first neurotrophic factor, nerve growth factor (NGF).
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Different mechanisms regulate PCD in the peripheral nervous system (PNS) versus the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In the PNS, innervation of the target is proportional to the amount of the target-released neurotrophic factors NGF and NT3.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Expression of neurotrophin receptors, TrkA and TrkC, is sufficient to induce apoptosis in the absence of their ligands.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Therefore, it is speculated that PCD in the PNS is dependent on the release of neurotrophic factors and thus follows the concept of the neurotrophic theory.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Programmed cell death in the CNS is not dependent on external growth factors but instead relies on intrinsically derived cues.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In the neocortex, a 4:1 ratio of excitatory to inhibitory interneurons is maintained by apoptotic machinery that appears to be independent of the environment.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Supporting evidence came from an experiment where interneuron progenitors were either transplanted into the mouse neocortex or cultured in vitro.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Transplanted cells died at the age of two weeks, the same age at which endogenous interneurons undergo apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Regardless of the size of the transplant, the fraction of cells undergoing apoptosis remained constant.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Furthermore, disruption of TrkB, a receptor for brain derived neurotrophic factor (Bdnf), did not affect cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It has also been shown that in mice null for the proapoptotic factor Bax (Bcl-2-associated X protein) a larger percentage of interneurons survived compared to wild type mice.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Together these findings indicate that programmed cell death in the CNS partly exploits Bax-mediated signaling and is independent of BDNF and the environment.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Apoptotic mechanisms in the CNS are still not well understood, yet it is thought that apoptosis of interneurons is a self-autonomous process.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Programmed cell death can be reduced or eliminated in the developing nervous system by the targeted deletion of pro-apoptotic genes or by the overexpression of anti-apoptotic genes.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The absence or reduction of PCD can cause serious anatomical malformations but can also result in minimal consequences depending on the gene targeted, neuronal population, and stage of development.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Excess progenitor cell proliferation that leads to gross brain abnormalities is often lethal, as seen in caspase-3 or caspase-9 knockout mice which develop exencephaly in the forebrain.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The brainstem, spinal cord, and peripheral ganglia of these mice develop normally, however, suggesting that the involvement of caspases in PCD during development depends on the brain region and cell type.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Knockout or inhibition of apoptotic protease activating factor 1 (APAF1), also results in malformations and increased embryonic lethality.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Manipulation of apoptosis regulator proteins Bcl-2 and Bax (overexpression of Bcl-2 or deletion of Bax) produces an increase in the number of neurons in certain regions of the nervous system such as the retina, trigeminal nucleus, cerebellum, and spinal cord.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] However, PCD of neurons due to Bax deletion or Bcl-2 overexpression does not result in prominent morphological or behavioral abnormalities in mice.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] For example, mice overexpressing Bcl-2 have generally normal motor skills and vision and only show impairment in complex behaviors such as learning and anxiety.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The normal behavioral phenotypes of these mice suggest that an adaptive mechanism may be involved to compensate for the excess neurons.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Learning about PCD in various species is essential in understanding the evolutionary basis and reason for apoptosis in development of the nervous system.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] During the development of the invertebrate nervous system, PCD plays different roles in different species.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The similarity of the asymmetric cell death mechanism in the nematode and the leech indicates that PCD may have an evolutionary significance in the development of the nervous system.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In the nematode, PCD occurs in the first hour of development leading to the elimination of 12% of non-gonadal cells including neuronal lineages.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Cell death in arthropods occurs first in the nervous system when ectoderm cells differentiate and one daughter cell becomes a neuroblast and the other undergoes apoptosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Furthermore, sex targeted cell death leads to different neuronal innervation of specific organs in males and females.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In *Drosophila*, PCD is essential in segmentation and specification during development.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] In contrast to invertebrates, the mechanism of programmed cell death is found to be more conserved in vertebrates.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Extensive studies performed on various vertebrates show that PCD of neurons and glia occurs in most parts of the nervous system during development.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It has been observed before and during synaptogenesis in the central nervous system as well as the peripheral nervous system.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] However, there are a few differences between vertebrate species.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] For example, mammals exhibit extensive arborization followed by PCD in the retina while birds do not.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Although synaptic refinement in vertebrate systems is largely dependent on PCD, other evolutionary mechanisms also play a role.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Programmed cell death in plants has a number of molecular similarities to animal apoptosis, but it also has differences, the most obvious being the presence of a cell wall and the lack of an immune system that removes the pieces of the dead cell.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Basic morphological and biochemical features of PCD have been conserved in both plant and animal kingdoms.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Specific types of plant cells carry out unique cell-death programs.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] These have common features with animal apoptosis—for instance, nuclear DNA degradation—but they also have their own peculiarities, such as nuclear degradation triggered by the collapse of the vacuole in tracheary elements of the xylem.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Leaver, of the Department of Plant Sciences, University of Oxford, carried out research on mutations in the mitochondrial genome of sun-flower cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Results of this research suggest that mitochondria play the same key role in vascular plant PCD as in other eukaryotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] During pollination, plants enforce self-incompatibility (**SI**) as an important means to prevent self-fertilization.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Research on the corn poppy (*Papaver rhoeas*) has revealed that proteins in the pistil on which the pollen lands, interact with pollen and trigger PCD in incompatible (i.e., *self*) pollen.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Franklin-Tong, also found that the response involves rapid inhibition of pollen-tube growth, followed by PCD.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The social slime mold *Dictyostelium discoideum* has the peculiarity of either adopting a predatory amoeba-like behavior in its unicellular form or coalescing into a mobile slug-like form when dispersing the spores that will give birth to the next generation.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The stalk is composed of dead cells that have undergone a type of PCD that shares many features of an autophagic cell-death: massive vacuoles forming inside cells, a degree of chromatin condensation, but no DNA fragmentation.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The structural role of the residues left by the dead cells is reminiscent of the products of PCD in plant tissue.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The occurrence of programmed cell death in protists is possible, but it remains controversial.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Some categorize death in those organisms as unregulated apoptosis-like cell death.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Biologists had long suspected that mitochondria originated from bacteria that had been incorporated as endosymbionts ("living together inside") of larger eukaryotic cells.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It was Lynn Margulis who from 1967 on championed this theory, which has since become widely accepted.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The most convincing evidence for this theory is the fact that mitochondria possess their own DNA and are equipped with genes and replication apparatus.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This evolutionary step would have been risky for the primitive eukaryotic cells, which began to engulf the energy-producing bacteria, as well as a perilous step for the ancestors of mitochondria, which began to invade their proto-eukaryotic hosts.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This process is still evident today, between human white blood cells and bacteria.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Most of the time, invading bacteria are destroyed by the white blood cells; however, it is not uncommon for the chemical warfare waged by prokaryotes to succeed, with the consequence known as infection by its resulting damage.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] One of these rare evolutionary events, about two billion years before the present, made it possible for certain eukaryotes and energy-producing prokaryotes to coexist and mutually benefit from their symbiosis.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Mitochondriate eukaryotic cells live poised between life and death, because mitochondria still retain their repertoire of molecules that can trigger cell suicide.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] It is not clear why apoptotic machinery is maintained in the extant unicellular organisms.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] This process has evolved to happen only when programmed to cells (such as feedback from neighbors, stress or DNA damage), mitochondria release caspase activators that trigger the cell-death-inducing biochemical cascade.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] As such, the cell suicide mechanism is now crucial to all of our lives.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Repair of DNA damages and apoptosis are two enzymatic processes essential for maintaining genome integrity in humans.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Cells that are deficient in DNA repair tend to accumulate DNA damages, and when such cells are also defective in apoptosis they tend to survive even with excess DNA damage.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Replication of DNA in such cells leads to mutations and these mutations may cause cancer (see Figure).
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] These dual role proteins tend to protect against development of cancer.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] The BCR-ABL oncogene has been found to be involved in the development of cancer in humans.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] c-Myc is involved in the regulation of apoptosis via its role in downregulating the Bcl-2 gene.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] Its role the disordered growth of tissue.
[src:apoptosis/programmed-cell-death] A molecular characteristic of metastatic cells is their altered expression of several apoptotic genes.
